          <abstract>
              <para>The project that underlies this dataset (Flora-On) was born as an attempt to concentrate and make easily and publicly available chorological, ecological, morphological and photographical information about the entire vascular flora of Portugal. It is fed constantly with new occurrence data from many active collaborators ( http://flora-on.pt/equipa.php ), who upload their weekly field observations to the database. Other scientific and technical projects have also contributed with data from their sampling campaigns.</para>
          </abstract>
          <funding>
              <para>The project receives no funding from any sources, and is entirely built and maintained with volunteer work; however, some externally funded projects have contributed with data to this project. Maintenance costs of the web server are covered by the membership fees of the associates of Sociedade Portuguesa de Botânica (Botanical Society of Portugal).</para>
          </funding>
            <studyAreaDescription>
                <descriptor name="generic" citableClassificationSystem="false">
                    <descriptorValue>The area of mainland Portugal is about 89 015 km2 and it is situated in the Mediterranean biogeographic region. The largest part of the territory falls in the mediterranean macrobioclimate and a small area in the north fits in the temperate macrobioclimate. Orography is mostly gentle in the southern part and rugged in the northern part, where the highest peak is located (1991 m above sea level).</descriptorValue>
                </descriptor>
            </studyAreaDescription>
            <designDescription>
                <description>
                    <para>The project aims to provide users the most up-to-date data on Portuguese flora, through a set of interactive tools to visualize, query and explore the data.
Highlights include: 1) a Bioclimatic Explorer, which allows projecting species occurrences (or occurrences of a compound query) in a climatic space ( http://www.flora-on.pt/#b ); 2) an interactive multiple-way identification key ( http://www.flora-on.pt/#z ); 3) an innovative WebGIS, allowing to overlay distribution layers not only for individual species but also richness-graduated layers made from compound queries ( http://www.flora-on.pt/#w ); 4) an all-in-one search box, linked to the previous tools, which allows to search species by a vast array of keywords related to habitat, morphology, flowering date, altitudinal range, location, climatic preferences and names; and 5) a Web Feature Service, which serves always up-to-date distribution maps ( http://www.flora-on.pt/wfs ).

The project has currently occurrence data spread over the whole country, but intensively sampled areas are still limited to the more coastal regions and a few spots in the interior. On average, 50000 new occurrences are uploaded into Flora-On each year. This dataset will thus be updated on a regular basis.</para>
                </description>
            </designDescription>
      </project>
